         <abstract>
            <p>This paper develops a methodology permitting financial managers and corporate debt issuers to accurately value a stream of contingent cash flows or claims that depend on the history and current levels of interest rates. The theory corrects the weaknesses in previously advanced models: in particular, it preserves put-call parity, ensures the absence of single and multiple period riskless arbitrage opportunities, and produces yield curves and their movement over time that satisfy reasonable conditions. The model guarantees the consistent pricing of complex financial instruments involving partial option-like behavior, ranging from mortgage-backed securities, to single premium deferred annuities, to a large variety of debt instruments with contingent payments. The paper details the application of the methodology to the analysis and pricing of GNMAs.</p>
         </abstract>
